policy = {
  'title': 'EADC Noseband Policy',
  'images': ['image88.jpg', 'image89.jpg'],
  'paragraphs': [
    'The Equestrian Australia Dressage Committee (EADC) wishes to reiterate that the welfare of the horse is paramount in all that it does, whether developing rules for the sport or in the training of its dressage stewards and judges.',
    'Nosebands that are too tightly fitted, regardless of type, are never acceptable. Nosebands must never be used in such a way that they interfere with a horse\u2019s breathing. It must be possible to place at least one finger between the horse\u2019s cheek and the noseband \u2014 see the measuring illustrations below.',
    'Noseband checking is done by a steward, wearing two clean disposable gloves, either prior to or after the completion of a test. Not all nosebands are required to be checked if a visual assessment confirms the noseband is not too tight. If during a test the judge believes a noseband is too tight, they must at the end of the test instruct the rider to return to the gear check, and the steward must report back to the judge.',
    'Checking must be done with the greatest caution, as some horses are very touchy and sensitive \u2014 the safety and welfare of the horse and athlete are the highest priority. Any adjustment of equipment must be done by the rider or groom, not the steward.',
    'Riders failing to loosen a noseband on request from a steward or judge will be eliminated. If a noseband is deemed too tight by a steward in the warm-up and is not loosened when requested, a Yellow Warning Card will be issued.',
    'All bridles must have a throat lash (see National Rules 5.11 for the combined noseband and Micklem exceptions).',
  ],
}
